The forests of the world cover an area of about 5.4 billion hectares, or about 30% of the terrestrial surface of the globe. Forests cover about 308 million hectares of temperate and boreal forests, 1.6 billion hectares of tropical forests and 1.9 billion hectares of boreal and temperate grasslands. International trade will benefit both countries so why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market? The theory of comparative advantage suggests that countries should specialise in producing those things that they can produce more efficiently, and trade with others for the things that they are relatively less good at producing. However, this does not always happen. For example, some firms may lobby the government to impose tariffs on imported goods to protect their domestic market. This protectionism is usually counterproductive, so why do countries still persist with it? Countries have an incentive to use trade policy to protect domestic firms from foreign competition.
